WwxMTE3Njk5OTUx', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor-kafka/labels/status/need-decision', 'name': 'status/need-decision', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False, 'description': 'This needs team attention and discussion'}, {'id': 2791573428, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyNzkxNTczNDI4', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor-kafka/labels/for/user-attention', 'name': 'for/user-attention', 'color': 'C5DEF5', 'default': False, 'description': 'This issue needs user attention (feedback, rework, etc...)'}], 'state': 'open', 'locked': False, 'assignee': None, 'assignees': [], 'milestone': None, 'comments': 4, 'created_at': '2021-09-10T21:39:32Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-19T15:21:33Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '<!--- Provide a general summary of the issue in the Title above -->

Maybe this is just an issue with our specific implementation of this, but we're seeing unexpected behavior that's causing problems when rebalancing happens.

In our current process, we're using concurrent processing with partition-based ordering with the intention being to consume each partition sequentially on the same set of threads, as described in the reactor-kafka docs. In our process, we check to see if we're assigned the partition before processing--if so, we continue, if not, we return--and we also check after processing if we still have the partition assigned. If we have the partition assigned after processing, we make the manual acknowledgement, and reactor will make the commits when it needs to. What we're seeing is that when partitions are revoked, the Flux continues to have messages. The problem here lies in the asynchronicity, if a partition is re-assigned a partition while the Flux is still processing a message, we will process it successfully, see that we own the partition, and acknowledge the offset, which will acknowledge all of the offsets before, even though we didn't actually process those messages. Sample code is shown below, but it appears to be a race condition where the Flux is not re-initialized (or purged) when Kafka takes the partitions, even though they should be.

<!--- /!\ Make sure to follow the Contribution Guidelines, notably for security issues and questions:
https://github.com/reactor/.github/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md
https://pivotal.io/security
https://github.com/reactor/.github/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#question-do-you-have-a-question
-->

## Expected Behavior
<!--- Tell us what you think should happen. -->

Flux is drained/reinitialized when Kafka revokes partitions. Docs for ReceiverOptions indicate that `when group management is used, revoke listeners are invoked before every rebalance operation`, which if true, the above behavior is not in line with Kafka's docs for the `ConsumerRebalanceListener`, which indicate that `in eager rebalancing, it will always be called at the start of a rebalance and after the consumer stops fetching data.`

## Actual Behavior
<!--- Tell us what happens instead of the expected behavior. -->

Messages persist on the Flux and are successfully processed, which will cause a race condition if the same partition is later re-assigned.

## Steps to Reproduce
<!---Provide a link to a live example, or an unambiguous set of steps to
reproduce this bug, eg. a unit test. Include code to reproduce, if relevant.
Most projects use JUnit5 now (like in snippet below; otherwise use JUnit4).
-->

Our consumer is as follows:
```java
ReceiverOptions<Integer, String> options = ReceiverOptions.create(props);
receiverOptions = options.subscription(getTopicAndReplica(topic))
        .addAssignListener(partitions -> {
            assignedPartitions = partitions;
            log.info("{} Partitions Assigned {}", name, AOUtilities.printPartitions(partitions));
        })
        .addRevokeListener(partitions -> {
            assignedPartitions.clear();
            log.info("{} Partitions Revoked {}", name, AOUtilities.printPartitions(partitions));
        })
        .commitInterval(Duration.ofSeconds(1))
        .commitBatchSize(1)
        .closeTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(30))
        .pollTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(5));
        
receiver = KafkaReceiver.create(receiverOptions);

scheduler = Schedulers.newBoundedElastic(Schedulers.DEFAULT_BOUNDED_ELASTIC_SIZE, Integer.MAX_VALUE, schedulerThreadName, 60, false);

receiver.receive().groupBy(m -> m.receiverOffset().topicPartition())
      .flatMap(partitionFlux -> partitionFlux.publishOn(scheduler)
                                  .map(r -> {
                                      if (isAssignedPartition(r)) {
                                          eventConsumer.consumeEvent(r, name);
                                          if (isAssignedPartition(r)) {
                                              r.receiverOffset().acknowledge();
                                              updatePartitionOffset(r);
                                          } else {
                                              log.info("Event Dropped: Partition {} not exists with {} anymore after processed. Results a duplicate", r.receiverOffset(), name);
                                          }
                                          return r;
                                      } else {
                                          log.info("Event Dropped: Partition {} not exists with {} anymore", r.receiverOffset(), name);
                                          return Mono.just(r);
                                      }
                                  })
      )
      .subscribe();
```

The `isAssignedPartition()` method simply checks the in-memory `assignedPartitions` map, which you'll see gets set and cleared on assignment and revocation respectively.

To reproduce, you can run two instances of this same consumer within the same consumer group. Ensure that the consumer group has plenty of lag. Keep one of the instances on at all times, and cycle the other one on and off repeatedly. When this happens, occasionally messages will be consumed by the primary instance between the time that partitions are revoked and before new partitions are assigned, which the logs below show:

