```java
@Retryable(include = { ... }, exclude = { ... }, rethrow = true, recoverAllOthers = true)
```
If `rethrow` is true and `recoverAllOthers` is false (default), all excluded + not included exceptions are rethrown immediately.

If `rethrow` is true and `recoverAllOthers` is true, all excluded exceptions are rethrown immediately, all others (not in `include` or `exclude` and not a subclass of any of those) go straight to the recover method (if one matches, or rethrown otherwise).

This would probably need changes to the classifier - in another project I subclassed it and made `getClassified()` public so I could check if a particular exception is explicitly classified; I see no reason we can't make it public (or at least a version that returns an unmodifiable map).

I am not married to the name `recoverAllOthers`, I am just concerned about adding a third type of "exclude" classes; we already have two - `exclude` and not `include`.
